  <!-- ═══ SECTION 2: DATA VAULT MODELLING ═══ -->
  <section class="section" style="animation-delay: 0.15s;">
    <div class="section-label">Section 02</div>
    <h2>Data Vault Modelling</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">
      Data Vault provides the persistence pattern for the platform's entity model: stable Hubs for business keys,
      Satellites for descriptive attributes that change over time, and Links for the relationships between them.
      This maps directly onto the entity resolution pipeline already in production.
    </p>

    <div class="vault-grid">

      <div class="vault-card">
        <div class="vault-type">Hub · Stable Identity</div>
        <h3>Business Keys</h3>
        <p>Hubs are the entities that exist independently of any single transaction. In FA, these are the things every system needs to reference consistently.</p>
        <div class="vault-examples">
          <strong>Examples</strong><br>
          HUB_FUND (ISIN / LEI / internal ID)<br>
          HUB_INVESTOR (LEI / KYC ID)<br>
          HUB_INSTRUMENT (ISIN / CUSIP)<br>
          HUB_COUNTERPARTY (LEI)
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="vault-card">
        <div class="vault-type">Satellite · Versioned Attributes</div>
        <h3>Time-Varying Detail</h3>
        <p>Satellites carry the descriptive data that changes — and they preserve history natively, which matters for regulatory restatements and audit trails.</p>
        <div class="vault-examples">
          <strong>Examples</strong><br>
          SAT_FUND_NAV (per valuation point)<br>
          SAT_FUND_DOMICILE (regulatory changes)<br>
          SAT_INVESTOR_KYC (refresh cycles)<br>
          SAT_INSTRUMENT_PRICING (per pricing source)
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="vault-card">
        <div class="vault-type">Link · Relationships</div>
        <h3>Entity Connections</h3>
        <p>Links capture the relationships between Hubs without forcing a hierarchy. This is what makes the model resilient to organisational change without schema rework.</p>
        <div class="vault-examples">
          <strong>Examples</strong><br>
          LNK_INVESTOR_FUND (subscription)<br>
          LNK_FUND_INSTRUMENT (holdings)<br>
          LNK_FUND_COUNTERPARTY (depositary, etc.)<br>
          LNK_FUND_FAMILY (umbrella ↔ sub-fund)
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="vault-card">
        <div class="vault-type">Where it shows up</div>
        <h3>Entity Resolution Pipeline</h3>
        <p>The existing entity resolution pipeline (Medallion / Data Vault architecture, three operating modes) is the production implementation of this pattern. It reconciles inconsistent identifiers across upstream systems before they reach the Builder.</p>
        <div class="vault-examples">
          <strong>Modes</strong><br>
          Live (LLM-assisted resolution)<br>
          Generate-Prompt (offline, manual)<br>
          Offline (deterministic only)
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 3: DATA MESH ALIGNMENT ═══ -->
  <section class="section" style="animation-delay: 0.2s;">
    <div class="section-label">Section 03</div>
    <h2>Data Mesh Alignment</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">
      Dehghani's four Data Mesh principles map onto the platform components without strain. The platform was not
      built to be a Data Mesh — it converged on the same answers because the same underlying problems
      (autonomy, governance, discoverability) apply.
    </p>

    <div class="mesh-grid">

      <div class="mesh-cell">
        <div class="mesh-num">PRINCIPLE 01</div>
        <h4>Domain ownership</h4>
        <p>The Fund Rules Ontology is owned by the regulatory and product teams, not data engineering. It is the legal source of truth for calculations, and it is versioned and tested like code.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="mesh-cell">
        <div class="mesh-num">PRINCIPLE 02</div>
        <h4>Data as a product</h4>
        <p>The Tool Library is the canonical example. Every approved calculation is a discoverable, documented, versioned, reusable product with a clear owner — not just a script in a repo.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="mesh-cell">
        <div class="mesh-num">PRINCIPLE 03</div>
        <h4>Self-serve infrastructure</h4>
        <p>The Builder generates calculation code on demand. The Constitution validates it. Domain experts compose new calculations without going through a central data team. The platform is the infrastructure.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="mesh-cell">
        <div class="mesh-num">PRINCIPLE 04</div>
        <h4>Federated governance</h4>
        <p>The Constitution Agent enforces global invariants (double-entry, LPA limits, ACID, dimensional integrity) while domain teams own their specific rules. Central guardrails, federated content.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 4: HOW (Q&A) ═══ -->
  <section class="section" style="animation-delay: 0.25s;">
    <div class="section-label">Section 04</div>
    <h2>The HOW</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">
      The technical questions that data engineers from a Snowflake or Databricks background ask first.
      Direct answers, with the platform's actual implementations.
    </p>

    <div class="qa-list">

      <div class="qa">
        <div class="qa-q">Q · How do you handle conflicting business keys across upstream systems?</div>
        <div class="qa-a">
          The <strong>entity resolution pipeline</strong> runs before the Builder ever sees the data. It uses a Medallion-staged approach with deterministic matching first (LEI, ISIN), then a confidence-scored fuzzy stage, then optional LLM-assisted disambiguation in <code>live</code> mode. The output is a <strong>canonical Hub key</strong> — the rest of the platform never sees the raw inconsistency.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa">
        <div class="qa-q">Q · How is change history preserved? Can you restate a prior NAV?</div>
        <div class="qa-a">
          Satellites are append-only with a <code>load_dts</code> timestamp. The Posting Agent writes immutable entries. To restate, the Builder generates a new calculation script targeting the historical valuation point; the Constitution validates it; the Human Gate approves the restatement; the Posting Agent writes a <strong>new Satellite row</strong> with full provenance back to the original. Nothing is overwritten.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa">
        <div class="qa-q">Q · How do you guarantee transformation consistency across runs?</div>
        <div class="qa-a">
          This is what the <strong>Tool Library</strong> exists for. Once a calculation is approved, the script is content-hashed and stored. Future requests for the same calculation type retrieve the verified script — they do not regenerate it. Layer 2 of the defence stack runs <strong>regression tests</strong> against the precedent on every reuse. Drift is caught before it reaches the ledger.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa">
        <div class="qa-q">Q · How do you handle schema drift in upstream files?</div>
        <div class="qa-a">
          The Reader produces <strong>canonical JSON</strong> with confidence scores per field. Schema drift in source files manifests as low-confidence extractions, which the Anomaly Agent and Human Gate catch before they propagate. <strong>The platform never depends on upstream systems to change</strong> — that's a deliberate principle.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa">
        <div class="qa-q">Q · How do you do data quality?</div>
        <div class="qa-a">
          Three layers, in order of cost. <strong>Bronze</strong>: confidence scoring at extraction. <strong>Silver</strong>: Constitution validation (double-entry, LPA limits, ACID, dimensional integrity) plus the six defence layers. <strong>Gold</strong>: Anomaly Agent ML-based outlier detection plus mandatory Human Gate for novelty. Every layer is auditable.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa">
        <div class="qa-q">Q · How does this scale beyond fund administration?</div>
        <div class="qa-a">
          The Reader, Builder, Constitution, and Tool Library are <strong>domain-parameterised</strong> — they take the Fund Rules Ontology as input. Swap the ontology for transfer agency rules, depositary rules, or insurance accounting rules, and the same architecture applies. The defence layers and Human Gate are domain-agnostic.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

